<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="309" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,258,1507]" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,342,1086,1111]" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera" authorityYear="2017" box="[540,661,1086,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convolutus">
<emphasis box="[540,661,1086,1110]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">convolutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, meaning rolled or twisted or spirally, referring to the curled shape of antennal segment IV.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="309" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,258,1507]" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1158,1183]" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Stein)" authorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[637,843,1158,1183]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moritzii">
<emphasis box="[637,758,1159,1182]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">A. moritzii</emphasis>
(Stein)
</taxonomicName>
in that both species have the anterior and posterior lobes of the pronotum uniformly shiny reddish brown to shiny brownish castaneous. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Stein" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[1118,1388,1195,1219]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moritzii">
<emphasis box="[1118,1388,1195,1219]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">Alloeorhynchus moritzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by having the corium shiny yellow with apical third reddish brown; the apex of the scutellum is reddish brown; the legs are yellow; and antennal segment IV is pale castaneous orange. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2017" authorityName="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera" authorityYear="2017" box="[1180,1333,1267,1291]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convolutus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1180,1333,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">A. convolutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1342,1432,1267,1290]" pageId="4" pageNumber="309" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, the corium is entirely shiny reddish brown; the apex of the scutellum is yellow; the legs are shiny castaneous orange (tarsi pale castaneous orange); and antennal segment IV is yellowish white with basal third and apex brown. 
<taxonomicName authority="Stal" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1873" box="[151,528,1374,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="309" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittativentris">
<emphasis box="[151,477,1374,1398]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">Alloeorhynchus vittativentris</emphasis>
Stål
</taxonomicName>
described from 
<collectingCountry box="[716,826,1374,1399]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">Colombia</collectingCountry>
and later recorded from 
<collectingRegion box="[1113,1202,1375,1398]" country="Panama" name="Panama" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">
<collectingCountry box="[1113,1202,1375,1398]" name="Panama" pageId="4" pageNumber="309">Panama</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
has the anterior and posterior lobes of pronotum and the clavus and corium uniformly brownish castaneous, but the legs are pale yellow and the apex of scutellum is dark reddish brown to black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
